Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG TO HIR TRANSLATOR - Production Translation Frontend
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translates Erlang AST to HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation)
Note: Handles: actor model, message passing, pattern matching, guards,
Note: concurrent functional programming, fault tolerance
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_lexer.runa" as ErlangLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIRNodes
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as DictPrim

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATION CONTEXT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translation context bundles every piece of mutable state the Erlang
translator needs: the current module name, its exported function set,
record/type indexes for resolution, a local-variable type environment,
an accumulating error list, and a counter for synthetic temp names.
Bundling avoids threading many parameters through every translate_*
call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Field-based struct. current_module is the module being translated.
exported_functions is a list of {name, arity} pairs read from the
`-export(...)` attribute. records/types/local_vars are dictionaries
populated as declarations are encountered. errors collects diagnostic
strings without aborting translation. next_temp_id is a monotonic
counter used by generate_temp_var.
@End Implementation

Type called "ErlangTranslationContext":
    current_module as String
    exported_functions as List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]  Note: {name, arity}
    records as Dictionary[String, ErlangRecord]
    types as Dictionary[String, ErlangTypeDecl]
    local_vars as Dictionary[String, HIRType]
    errors as List[String]
    next_temp_id as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructs an empty context bound to the supplied module name. All
collections start empty; populating them is the responsibility of
translate_erlang_module_to_hir as it walks the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds the ErlangTranslationContext struct; sets current_module from
the parameter; initialises exported_functions/errors as empty lists,
records/types/local_vars as empty dictionaries, and next_temp_id to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_translation_context" that takes module_name as String returns ErlangTranslationContext:
    Let ctx be a value of type ErlangTranslationContext
    Set ctx.current_module to module_name
    Set ctx.exported_functions to proc list_create from ListPrim
    Set ctx.records to a dictionary containing nothing
    Set ctx.types to a dictionary containing nothing
    Set ctx.local_vars to a dictionary containing nothing
    Set ctx.errors to proc list_create from ListPrim
    Set ctx.next_temp_id to 0
    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generates fresh synthetic variable names for cases where the
translator needs to bind a value (e.g. for desugaring pattern matches
into explicit dispatch). Names use a `$erlang_temp_` prefix so they
cannot collide with Erlang identifiers (which don't allow `$`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Concatenates "$erlang_temp_" with the string form of next_temp_id,
then increments next_temp_id so the next call produces a fresh name.
Returns the new name.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_temp_var" that takes ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns String:
    Note: Bind the field handle before the StringPrim call (stage1 mis-evaluates
    Note: a `obj.field` proc-call argument).
    Let current_temp_id be ctx.next_temp_id
    Let temp_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with current_temp_id
    Let temp_name be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "$erlang_temp_", temp_id_str
    Set ctx.next_temp_id to ctx.next_temp_id plus 1
    Return temp_name
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Module translation walks attributes first to extract the exported-functions
list (the only attribute with HIR-level effect; others are pre-processor or
documentation), then indexes records and types into name-keyed maps so later
expression translation can resolve record/type references in constant time.
Function translation is the final pass because functions may refer to
records and types declared anywhere in the module, even after the function
itself - Erlang's parser collects declarations across the whole module
before semantic processing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_erlang_module_to_hir" that takes erl_module as ErlangModule returns HIRModule:
    Let ctx be create_translation_context with erl_module.module_name

    Note: Process module attributes to extract exports and metadata. The
    Note: attr_values handle is bound to a local before the ListPrim calls
    Note: (stage1 mis-evaluates a field-access proc-call argument inside a
    Note: compound boolean condition).
    Let module_attributes be erl_module.attributes
    For Each attr as ErlangAttribute in module_attributes:
        Let module_attr_type be attr.attr_type
        Let module_attr_vals be attr.attr_values
        Let module_attr_vals_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with module_attr_vals
        If module_attr_type is equal to "export" and module_attr_vals_count is greater than 0:
            Let export_list be proc list_get from ListPrim with module_attr_vals, 0
            Set ctx.exported_functions to export_list
        End If
    End For

    Note: Index records by name. The records/types/functions collections are
    Note: bound to locals before iterating (stage1 mis-evaluates a field-access
    Note: collection in a For Each header). The dict handle and the key are each
    Note: bound to locals before the dictionary set, because stage1 mis-evaluates
    Note: a `obj.field at key obj2.field` compound lvalue (both the target dict
    Note: field-access and the inline key field-access).
    Let ctx_records be ctx.records
    Let module_records be erl_module.records
    For Each record as ErlangRecord in module_records:
        Let record_key be record.name
        Set ctx_records at key record_key to record
    End For

    Note: Index types by name
    Let ctx_types be ctx.types
    Let module_types be erl_module.types
    For Each type_decl as ErlangTypeDecl in module_types:
        Let type_key be type_decl.name
        Set ctx_types at key type_key to type_decl
    End For

    Note: Translate all functions
    Let hir_functions be a list containing nothing

    Let module_functions be erl_module.functions
    For Each erl_func as ErlangFunction in module_functions:
        Let hir_func be translate_function with erl_func, ctx
        Add hir_func to end of hir_functions
    End For

    Note: Create HIR module
    Note: Field order mirrors the backend's HIRModule type definition
    Note: (name, exports, functions, types, imports, records) so the produced
    Note: struct layout is byte-compatible with what
    Note: generate_erlang_module_from_hir reads through its typed HIRModule view.
    Note: The original -record declarations are carried verbatim as the trailing
    Note: records field so the backend can re-emit them; the dict-indexed
    Note: ctx.records is only for record_create field resolution during lowering.
    Let module_records_list be erl_module.records
    Let hir_module be a value of type HIRModule with
        name as erl_module.module_name,
        exports as ctx.exported_functions,
        functions as hir_functions,
        types as a list containing nothing,
        imports as a list containing nothing,
        records as module_records_list

    Return hir_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Erlang functions are syntactically a sequence of clauses sharing a name+arity,
each with its own pattern list and optional guard sequence. HIR has no native
multi-clause construct, so we collapse to a single function whose body is a
pattern-matching dispatch. We special-case the common single-clause-no-guards
shape with a direct body translation to avoid wrapping trivial functions in
an unconditional if-statement that the optimiser would have to undo. The
exported flag is set by walking ctx.exported_functions and matching on
name+arity, the same identity Erlang uses for export resolution.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function" that takes erl_func as ErlangFunction, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRFunction:
    Note: Erlang functions can have multiple clauses with different patterns
    Note: Translate to single HIR function with pattern matching dispatch

    Let func_name be erl_func.name
    Let arity be erl_func.arity

    Note:
    Create the parameter list. Names are derived from the clause patterns
    (compute_parameter_names) rather than synthesised as arg0/arg1, so the
    emitted clause head binds exactly the variables the body references. A
    position keeps the source name when every clause agrees on a simple
    variable there; otherwise it falls back to arg{i} and the dispatch path
    rebinds per-clause. The clauses handle is bound to a local before the
    helper call (stage1 mis-evaluates a field-access proc-call argument).
    :End Note
    Let parameters be a list containing nothing
    Let param_types be a list containing nothing

    Let clauses_for_names be erl_func.clauses
    Set parameters to compute_parameter_names with clauses_for_names, arity

    For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
        Note: Erlang is dynamically typed - use Any type
        Let param_type be create_hir_type with "any", a list containing nothing
        Add param_type to end of param_types
    End For

    Note: Create function signature
    Let return_type be create_hir_type with "any", a list containing nothing

    Note: Build function body
    Let body be a list containing nothing

    Note: If single clause without guards or patterns, translate directly. The
    Note: clauses handle is bound to a local before the ListPrim calls (stage1
    Note: mis-evaluates a field-access proc-call argument).
    Let func_clauses be erl_func.clauses
    Let func_clause_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with func_clauses
    If func_clause_count is equal to 1:
        Let clause_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with func_clauses, 0
        Let clause be clause_raw of type ErlangFunctionClause

        Let has_complex_patterns be false
        Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        For Each pattern as ErlangExpression in clause_patterns:
            If not is_simple_variable_pattern with pattern:
                Set has_complex_patterns to true
                Break
            End If
        End For

        Let clause_guards be clause.guards
        Let guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
        If not has_complex_patterns and guard_count is equal to 0:
            Note: Simple case - just translate body
            Let clause_body be clause.body
            Set body to translate_expressions with clause_body, ctx
        Otherwise:
            Note: Complex patterns or guards - build match dispatch
            Set body to translate_clauses_with_dispatch with func_clauses, parameters, ctx
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: Multiple clauses - build match dispatch
        Set body to translate_clauses_with_dispatch with func_clauses, parameters, ctx
    End If

    Note: Check if function is exported. The export_info dict lookups are bound
    Note: to locals before the compound comparison (stage1 mis-evaluates a dict
    Note: `at key` subexpression nested inside a boolean condition).
    Let is_exported be false
    Let ctx_exports be ctx.exported_functions
    For Each export_info in ctx_exports:
        Let export_name be proc get from DictPrim with export_info, "name"
        Let export_arity be proc get from DictPrim with export_info, "arity"
        If export_name is equal to func_name and export_arity is equal to arity:
            Set is_exported to true
            Break
        End If
    End For

    Let hir_func be a value of type HIRFunction with
        name as func_name,
        parameters as parameters,
        param_types as param_types,
        return_type as return_type,
        body as body,
        is_public as is_exported

    Return hir_func
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifies patterns that bind a name (or the wildcard) without performing any
structural destructuring. The result drives translate_function's fast path:
single-clause functions whose patterns are ALL simple variables can skip the
match-dispatch machinery entirely. Underscore is treated as simple even
though it is technically an atom because it never fails to match and
contributes no bindings.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_simple_variable_pattern" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if pattern is just a simple variable (no destructuring)
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Return true
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let pattern_data be pattern.expr_data
        Let pattern_atom_value be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "value"
        If pattern_atom_value is equal to "_":
            Return true  Note: Underscore wildcard
        End If
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the source variable name a simple-variable pattern binds, or the empty
string when the pattern is not a plain variable (a literal, the wildcard, or a
destructuring shape). Used by compute_parameter_names to decide whether a
formal-parameter position can adopt the original source identifier so the
emitted clause head binds exactly the name the body references - eliminating
the unbound-variable defect of synthetic arg0/arg1 heads. The wildcard "_" is
deliberately reported as non-nameable (empty) because adopting "_" as the
parameter name would make body references to a real binding unresolvable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "simple_variable_pattern_name" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression returns String:
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let pattern_data be pattern.expr_data
        Let var_name be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "name"
        If var_name is equal to "_":
            Return ""
        End If
        Return var_name
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Derives the HIR formal-parameter name list from the function's clauses so the
emitted Erlang clause head binds the variables the body actually references.
Erlang functions carry one pattern list per clause; the HIR collapses every
clause into a single function with one shared parameter list. For a position i
we adopt the original source variable name when EVERY clause presents a simple
variable pattern at i AND they all agree on the same name; this is the common
idiomatic case (e.g. classify(X) ... classify(X), helper(N), add(A, B)) and it
makes the head binding match the body's references with no rebinding required.
When the clauses disagree on the name, or any clause destructures at that
position, the name cannot be shared safely, so we fall back to the synthetic
arg{i}; the dispatch path then rebinds each clause's own simple-variable name
to arg{i} inside that clause's body (see translate_clauses_with_dispatch), and
destructuring positions are matched structurally by build_pattern_match.
@End Reasoning
Process called "compute_parameter_names" that takes clauses as List[ErlangFunctionClause], arity as Integer returns List[String]:
    Let names be a list containing nothing
    Let clause_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses

    Let pos be 0
    While pos is less than arity:
        Note:
        Determine the shared name for this position. Start undecided; the first
        clause proposes a candidate, each subsequent clause must agree or the
        position degrades to the synthetic arg name. A non-simple-variable
        pattern at any clause also forces the synthetic name.
        :End Note
        Let candidate be ""
        Let usable be true
        Let ci be 0
        While ci is less than clause_count:
            Let clause_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, ci
            Let clause be clause_raw of type ErlangFunctionClause
            Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
            Let pattern_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_patterns
            If pos is less than pattern_count:
                Let pattern_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, pos
                Let pattern be pattern_raw of type ErlangExpression
                Let this_name be simple_variable_pattern_name with pattern
                If this_name is equal to "":
                    Set usable to false
                Otherwise:
                    If candidate is equal to "":
                        Set candidate to this_name
                    Otherwise:
                        Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with candidate, this_name
                        If same is equal to 0:
                            Set usable to false
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set usable to false
            End If
            Set ci to ci plus 1
        End While

        Let chosen be ""
        If usable is equal to true and candidate is not equal to "":
            Set chosen to candidate
        Otherwise:
            Let pos_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with pos
            Set chosen to proc string_concat from StringPrim with "arg", pos_str
        End If
        Add chosen to end of names
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    Return names
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-clause functions become an if-chain where each clause becomes one
if-statement. We walk clauses in source order because Erlang's first-match
semantics requires the first matching clause to win - converting to nested
else-if would also work but the flat sequence is easier for downstream
optimisers to flatten or convert into a switch. Every dispatch chain
terminates with an erlang:error(function_clause) call so the runtime
behaviour mirrors what the Erlang VM produces when no clause matches.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_clauses_with_dispatch" that takes clauses as List[ErlangFunctionClause], parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns List[HIRStatement]:
    Note: Build pattern matching dispatch for multiple clauses
    Let body be a list containing nothing

    Note: Generate nested if-else chain or match statement for clauses. The
    Note: clause count is computed once into a local and the loop runs as a
    Note: While: the stage1 codegen mis-evaluates a `For ... to <proc call>
    Note: minus 1` range bound.
    Let clause_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than clause_total:
        Let clause_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i
        Let clause be clause_raw of type ErlangFunctionClause

        Note: Build condition for this clause (pattern matching + guards)
        Let clause_condition be build_clause_condition with clause, parameters, ctx

        Note: Translate clause body. The clause handle is cast to its struct type
        Note: so the body field-access reads at the correct offset; a list_get
        Note: result is Integer-typed and stage1 computes a stale offset for an
        Note: `obj.field` access on an unannotated Integer handle.
        Let clause_body_exprs be clause.body
        Let clause_body be translate_expressions with clause_body_exprs, ctx

        Note:
        Rebind clause-local simple-variable parameter names to the shared formal
        when they differ. compute_parameter_names only adopts a source name at a
        position when EVERY clause agrees on it, so when a position fell back to
        the synthetic arg{i} (or another clause's name was chosen) this clause's
        own variable would otherwise be unbound in its body. Prepend `Var = argI`
        for each position where this clause's simple-variable name differs from
        the chosen formal name. The bindings precede the body so the body's
        references resolve. Built into a fresh list and concatenated so the body
        order is binding(s)-then-original-statements.
        :End Note
        Let rebind_clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let rebind_pattern_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with rebind_clause_patterns
        Let rebind_stmts be a list containing nothing
        Let rb be 0
        While rb is less than rebind_pattern_count:
            Let rebind_pattern_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with rebind_clause_patterns, rb
            Let rebind_pattern be rebind_pattern_raw of type ErlangExpression
            Let clause_var_name be simple_variable_pattern_name with rebind_pattern
            If clause_var_name is not equal to "":
                Let formal_name be proc list_get from ListPrim with parameters, rb
                Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with clause_var_name, formal_name
                If names_match is equal to 0:
                    Let rebind_target be create_hir_var with clause_var_name
                    Let rebind_value be create_hir_var with formal_name
                    Let rebind_stmt be create_hir_assign with rebind_target, rebind_value
                    Add rebind_stmt to end of rebind_stmts
                End If
            End If
            Set rb to rb plus 1
        End While

        Let rebind_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with rebind_stmts
        If rebind_count is greater than 0:
            For Each body_stmt in clause_body:
                Add body_stmt to end of rebind_stmts
            End For
            Set clause_body to rebind_stmts
        End If

        Note: Create conditional block. The if_stmt local is hoisted above the
        Note: branch so both the first-clause and subsequent-clause paths write a
        Note: live slot; stage1 leaves a `Set` target null when the variable was
        Note: only `Let`-declared inside a sibling branch (the i=0 arm), which the
        Note: i>=1 iterations then dereference -> segfault.
        Let if_stmt be 0
        If i is equal to 0:
            Note: First clause - create if statement
            Set if_stmt to create_hir_if with clause_condition, clause_body, a list containing nothing
            Add if_stmt to end of body
        Otherwise:
            Note: Subsequent clauses become further dispatch tests. The full
            Note: guard semantics (conjunction within a sequence, disjunction
            Note: across sequences) are already folded into clause_condition by
            Note: build_clause_condition, so the body is emitted directly as the
            Note: then-branch with no additional guard wrapping.
            Set if_stmt to create_hir_if with clause_condition, clause_body, a list containing nothing
            Add if_stmt to end of body
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add function_clause error if no clause matches
    Let function_clause_atom be create_hir_atom with "function_clause"
    Let function_clause_args be a list containing function_clause_atom
    Let error_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:error", function_clause_args
    Add error_call to end of body

    Return body
End Process

@Reasoning:
A clause matches when ALL its patterns match the corresponding parameters AND
all its guards succeed. We linearise that into a list of boolean expressions
(one per pattern check, one per guard expression) and AND them all together.
The AND chain is left-associative because Erlang guards short-circuit
left-to-right and our build_pattern_match emits checks that can fail safely
in any order. When no conditions exist (degenerate empty pattern list), we
return literal true so the if-statement degenerates to an unconditional
branch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "build_clause_condition" that takes clause as ErlangFunctionClause, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Build condition expression that checks if parameters match patterns and guards

    Let conditions be a list containing nothing

    Note: Build pattern matching conditions. Count computed once; While loop
    Note: (stage1 mis-evaluates a `For ... to <proc call> minus 1` bound).
    Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
    Let pattern_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_patterns
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than pattern_total:
        Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, i
        Let param_name be proc list_get from ListPrim with parameters, i
        Let pattern_check be build_pattern_match with pattern, param_name, ctx

        If pattern_check is not equal to 0:
            Add pattern_check to end of conditions
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note:
    Build the guard condition honouring Erlang's guard semantics: a clause's
    guard list is a DISJUNCTION of guard sequences (the ';' separator), and
    each sequence is a CONJUNCTION of guard tests (the ',' separator). So a
    clause guarded by `G1, G2 ; G3` succeeds when (G1 AND G2) OR G3. We build
    each sequence as a left-folded AND chain, then OR the sequences together,
    and add the single resulting guard expression to the conjunction with the
    pattern checks. An empty sequence contributes nothing; a clause with no
    guards adds no guard condition at all.
    :End Note
    Let guard_disjunction be 0
    Let clause_guard_seqs be clause.guards
    For Each guard_seq in clause_guard_seqs:
        Let seq_conjunction be 0
        For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
            Let guard_hir be translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
            If seq_conjunction is equal to 0:
                Set seq_conjunction to guard_hir
            Otherwise:
                Set seq_conjunction to create_hir_binary_op with "and", seq_conjunction, guard_hir
            End If
        End For

        If seq_conjunction is not equal to 0:
            If guard_disjunction is equal to 0:
                Set guard_disjunction to seq_conjunction
            Otherwise:
                Set guard_disjunction to create_hir_binary_op with "or", guard_disjunction, seq_conjunction
            End If
        End If
    End For

    If guard_disjunction is not equal to 0:
        Add guard_disjunction to end of conditions
    End If

    Note: Combine pattern checks and the guard expression with AND
    Let conditions_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with conditions
    If conditions_total is equal to 0:
        Return create_hir_bool with true
    End If

    If conditions_total is equal to 1:
        Return proc list_get from ListPrim with conditions, 0
    End If

    Note: Build AND chain (While loop; count precomputed)
    Let result be proc list_get from ListPrim with conditions, 0
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than conditions_total:
        Let next_cond be proc list_get from ListPrim with conditions, i
        Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, next_cond
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Translates an Erlang pattern into a boolean expression that tests whether a
target variable matches. Returns null (which the caller interprets as
"trivially true") for variable patterns and the wildcard, because those
patterns always succeed - but variable patterns also have a SIDE EFFECT of
recording the binding in ctx.local_vars so subsequent body translations can
resolve the variable. Literal patterns become equality comparisons; list and
tuple patterns recursively check structure (is_list / is_tuple + size match)
before recursing into elements. Element access uses erlang:nth (lists) or
erlang:element (1-indexed tuples) to mirror the canonical Erlang accessors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "build_pattern_match" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression, target_var as String, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Build condition expression that checks if target_var matches pattern

    Note: The pattern's expr_data dict is bound to a local once; a chained
    Note: `pattern.expr_data at key "..."` (field access THEN dict lookup in a
    Note: single expression) is mis-compiled by the stage1 codegen.
    Let pattern_data be pattern.expr_data

    Note: Variables written from more than one sibling branch (atom/integer/list/
    Note: tuple) are hoisted to function scope so every branch writes a live slot.
    Note: stage1 leaves a `Set` target null when the variable was only `Let`-
    Note: declared inside a different sibling branch, and dereferencing that null
    Note: in the next branch segfaults.
    Let target_expr be 0
    Let pattern_expr be 0
    Let elements be 0
    Let checks be 0
    Let result be 0
    Let elem_pattern be 0
    Let elem_temp be 0
    Let index_expr be 0
    Let elem_access be 0
    Let elem_check be 0

    Note: Simple variable or wildcard - always matches
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "name"

        If var_name is equal to "_":
            Return 0  Note: Wildcard always matches
        End If

        Note: Binding variable - record in context. The local_vars dict handle is
        Note: bound to a local before the set, because stage1 mis-evaluates a
        Note: `obj.field at key k` compound lvalue (the target dict field-access).
        Let any_type be create_hir_type with "any", a list containing nothing
        Let ctx_local_vars be ctx.local_vars
        Set ctx_local_vars at key var_name to any_type

        Return 0  Note: Variable pattern always matches
    End If

    Note: Atom literal - check equality
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "value"
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Set pattern_expr to create_hir_atom with atom_value
        Return create_hir_binary_op with "==", target_expr, pattern_expr
    End If

    Note: Integer literal - check equality
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "value"
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Set pattern_expr to create_hir_int with int_value
        Return create_hir_binary_op with "==", target_expr, pattern_expr
    End If

    Note: List pattern - check structure and elements
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Note:
        "elements"/"tail" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; an
        `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored handles returns 0 under stage1.
        :End Note
        Set elements to proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "elements"
        Let tail be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "tail"

        Note: Build list structure check
        Set checks to a list containing nothing

        Note: Check if target is a list
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Let is_list_check be create_hir_call with "erlang:is_list", a list containing target_expr
        Add is_list_check to end of checks

        Note: Check list length (if no tail). Element count precomputed once.
        Let elements_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with elements
        If tail is equal to 0 and elements_total is greater than 0:
            Let length_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:length", a list containing target_expr
            Let expected_len be create_hir_int with elements_total
            Let length_check be create_hir_binary_op with "==", length_call, expected_len
            Add length_check to end of checks
        End If

        Note: Check each element (While loop; stage1 mis-evaluates proc-call For bounds)
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than elements_total:
            Set elem_pattern to proc list_get from ListPrim with elements, i
            Set elem_temp to generate_temp_var with ctx

            Note: Extract element
            Set index_expr to create_hir_int with i
            Set elem_access to create_hir_call with "erlang:nth", a list containing index_expr, target_expr

            Note: Build element match
            Set elem_check to build_pattern_match with elem_pattern, elem_temp, ctx

            If elem_check is not equal to 0:
                Add elem_check to end of checks
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Combine all checks
        Let checks_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with checks
        If checks_total is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set result to proc list_get from ListPrim with checks, 0
        Set i to 1
        While i is less than checks_total:
            Let next_check be proc list_get from ListPrim with checks, i
            Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, next_check
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Return result
    End If

    Note: Tuple pattern - check structure
    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set elements to proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "elements"

        Set checks to a list containing nothing

        Note: Check if target is a tuple
        Set target_expr to create_hir_var with target_var
        Let is_tuple_check be create_hir_call with "erlang:is_tuple", a list containing target_expr
        Add is_tuple_check to end of checks

        Note: Check tuple size. Element count precomputed once.
        Let tuple_elements_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with elements
        Let size_call be create_hir_call with "erlang:tuple_size", a list containing target_expr
        Let expected_size be create_hir_int with tuple_elements_total
        Let size_check be create_hir_binary_op with "==", size_call, expected_size
        Add size_check to end of checks

        Note: Check each element (While loop; stage1 mis-evaluates proc-call For bounds)
        Let ti be 0
        While ti is less than tuple_elements_total:
            Set elem_pattern to proc list_get from ListPrim with elements, ti
            Set elem_temp to generate_temp_var with ctx

            Note: Extract element (1-indexed in Erlang)
            Set index_expr to create_hir_int with ti plus 1
            Set elem_access to create_hir_call with "erlang:element", a list containing index_expr, target_expr

            Note: Build element match
            Set elem_check to build_pattern_match with elem_pattern, elem_temp, ctx

            If elem_check is not equal to 0:
                Add elem_check to end of checks
            End If
            Set ti to ti plus 1
        End While

        Note: Combine all checks
        Let tuple_checks_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with checks
        Set result to proc list_get from ListPrim with checks, 0
        Set ti to 1
        While ti is less than tuple_checks_total:
            Let next_tuple_check be proc list_get from ListPrim with checks, ti
            Set result to create_hir_binary_op with "and", result, next_tuple_check
            Set ti to ti plus 1
        End While

        Return result
    End If

    Note: Default - no additional check needed
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translates a sequence of expressions (e.g. the body of a function clause or
case arm) into a list of HIR statements. The last expression in the list
typically becomes the implicit return value; we do NOT wrap it in an
explicit return here because the surrounding HIR function form treats the
final statement's value as the return automatically. Sequence semantics are
left-to-right with no early termination.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expressions" that takes exprs as List[ErlangExpression], ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns List[HIRStatement]:
    Let statements be a list containing nothing

    Note: The loop bound and the last-index test are bound to a local. The
    Note: stage1 codegen mis-evaluates a `For ... to <proc call> minus 1`
    Note: range bound (and re-evaluating the call each iteration is wasteful),
    Note: so the count is computed once.
    Let expr_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with exprs
    Let last_index be expr_total minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than expr_total:
        Let expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with exprs, i
        Let hir_expr be translate_expression with expr, ctx

        Note: Last expression is return value
        If i is equal to last_index:
            Let return_stmt be create_hir_return with hir_expr
            Add return_stmt to end of statements
        Otherwise:
            Note: Expression statement (side effect)
            Let expr_stmt be create_hir_expr_statement with hir_expr
            Add expr_stmt to end of statements
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return statements
End Process

@Reasoning:
The central expression dispatcher routes on expr.expr_type string. Leaf
literals (atom, var, integer, float, string, char) are handled inline
because each maps to a single HIR helper; composite forms delegate to
specialised translators (translate_list, translate_tuple, translate_binary,
etc.). The fallthrough at the end records an error in ctx.errors and emits
a sentinel HIR error node so the rest of the module can still translate even
when one expression is unrecognised - this is essential for the
research/debugging workflow where partial Erlang support is acceptable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expression" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note: Translate Erlang expression to HIR expression

    Note:
    Leaf node "value"/"name" entries are read through the canonical dictionary
    `get` primitive: the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of the
    incrementally-stored leaf value to a load that returns 0/empty, which would
    drop the atom text, variable name, or literal value.
    :End Note
    Note: Atom literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_data be expr.expr_data
        Let atom_value be proc get from DictPrim with atom_data, "value"
        Return create_hir_atom with atom_value
    End If

    Note: Variable reference
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_data be expr.expr_data
        Let var_name be proc get from DictPrim with var_data, "name"
        Return create_hir_var with var_name
    End If

    Note: Integer literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_data be expr.expr_data
        Let int_value be proc get from DictPrim with int_data, "value"
        Return create_hir_int with int_value
    End If

    Note: Float literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "float":
        Let float_data be expr.expr_data
        Let float_value be proc get from DictPrim with float_data, "value"
        Return create_hir_float with float_value
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "string":
        Let string_data be expr.expr_data
        Let str_value be proc get from DictPrim with string_data, "value"
        Return create_hir_string with str_value
    End If

    Note: Character literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "char":
        Let char_data be expr.expr_data
        Let char_value be proc get from DictPrim with char_data, "value"
        Return create_hir_char with char_value
    End If

    Note: List literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Return translate_list with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Tuple literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Return translate_tuple with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary literal
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "binary":
        Return translate_binary with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary operator
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "op":
        Return translate_binary_op with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Unary operator
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "unary_op":
        Return translate_unary_op with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Function call
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "call":
        Return translate_call with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Fun expression (anonymous function)
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "fun":
        Return translate_fun with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Case expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "case":
        Return translate_case with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: If expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "if":
        Return translate_if with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Receive expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "receive":
        Return translate_receive with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Try expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "try":
        Return translate_try with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Begin expression
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "begin":
        Return translate_begin with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: List comprehension
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "list_comprehension":
        Return translate_list_comprehension with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Binary comprehension
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "binary_comprehension":
        Return translate_binary_comprehension with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Record creation
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "record_create":
        Return translate_record_create with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Record access
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "record_access":
        Return translate_record_access with expr, ctx
    End If

    Note: Macro reference
    If expr.expr_type is equal to "macro":
        Let macro_data be expr.expr_data
        Let macro_name be proc get from DictPrim with macro_data, "name"
        Return create_hir_macro with macro_name
    End If

    Note: Default - unsupported expression
    Let unsupported_msg be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unsupported Erlang expression type: ", expr.expr_type
    Add unsupported_msg to end of ctx.errors
    Return create_hir_error with "unsupported_expression"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang lists come in two shapes: proper lists [e1, e2, e3] and improper lists
[H | T] where T is itself a list (or anything; Erlang permits improper
lists). Proper lists become a single HIR list literal. Improper lists are
built right-to-left as a chain of erlang:cons calls so the tail expression
appears at the rightmost position and each head prepends one element at a
time. This matches how Erlang's VM constructs lists internally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_list" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let list_data be expr.expr_data
    Note:
    "elements"/"tail" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored handles
    to a load that returns 0 even though they are present.
    :End Note
    Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with list_data, "elements"
    Let tail be proc get from DictPrim with list_data, "tail"

    Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let hir_elem be translate_expression with elem, ctx
        Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
    End For

    Note: Proper list (no tail)
    If tail is equal to 0:
        Return create_hir_list with hir_elements
    End If

    Note: Improper list with tail [H|T]
    Note: Build list cons operations
    Let result be translate_expression with tail, ctx

    Note: Build list from right to left. The element count is bound to a local
    Note: before computing the start index (stage1 mis-evaluates a `proc ...
    Note: minus 1` form applied inline to a proc-call result).
    Let hir_elements_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with hir_elements
    Let i be hir_elements_total minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let elem be proc list_get from ListPrim with hir_elements, i
        Set result to create_hir_call with "erlang:cons", a list containing elem, result
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuples are fixed-arity heterogeneous containers and translate directly to
an HIR tuple value. Element order matters and is preserved verbatim. Tuple
literals are first-class HIR primitives because too many downstream targets
have native tuple types for it to be worth lowering to a list-based form
here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_tuple" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let tuple_data be expr.expr_data
    Note:
    "elements" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the stage1
    codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored element list to a
    load that returns 0 even though it is present.
    :End Note
    Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with tuple_data, "elements"

    Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let hir_elem be translate_expression with elem, ctx
        Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
    End For

    Return create_hir_tuple with hir_elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binary syntax '<<S1, S2, ...>>' constructs a binary from a sequence
of segments, each carrying a value expression, an optional size, and a list
of type specifiers (integer/float/binary/utf8/etc., big/little endian,
signed/unsigned). We translate each segment into a dictionary preserving all
three components so backends can reproduce the bit-level layout exactly.
Specifiers are forwarded verbatim because Erlang's binary spec semantics are
intricate and the backend is in the best position to lower them.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data / segment entries are read through the canonical dictionary `get`
    primitive: the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these
    dict-literal-stored handles to a load that returns 0 even though the entries
    are present, which would feed null segment values into the translator.
    :End Note
    Let binary_data be expr.expr_data
    Let segments be proc get from DictPrim with binary_data, "segments"

    Note: Translate binary to HIR binary construction
    Let hir_segments be a list containing nothing

    For Each segment in segments:
        Let segment_value_expr be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "value"
        Let value be translate_expression with segment_value_expr, ctx
        Let size be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "size"
        Let specifiers be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "specifiers"

        Let hir_size be 0
        If size is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_size to translate_expression with size, ctx
        End If

        Let segment_info be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as value,
            "size" as hir_size,
            "specifiers" as specifiers
        End Dictionary

        Add segment_info to end of hir_segments
    End For

    Return create_hir_binary with hir_segments
End Process

@Reasoning:
Most Erlang binary operators map directly to HIR operator strings. Exceptions
require special HIR forms: '!' is the message-send operator (create_hir_send),
'=' is pattern match (create_hir_match), '++' and '--' are list operations
implemented as erlang:append / erlang:subtract calls because HIR has no
dedicated nodes for them. Other special spellings (=:=, =/=, andalso, orelse,
div, rem, b* bitwise) are rewritten to HIR's operator spelling without
semantic change. The default branch sets hir_op = operator so unrecognised
operators pass through (useful when Erlang adds new operator spellings the
translator hasn't been updated for).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    The op node's expr_data is a dictionary literal built in parse_expression
    ("operator"/"left"/"right"). Its "left"/"right" entries are read through the
    canonical dictionary primitive `get` rather than the `at key` operator: the
    stage1 codegen lowers the `at key` read of a dict-literal-stored expression
    handle to a load that returns 0 (the handle is present and correct, as the
    primitive `get` confirms), so reading the operand handles with `get`
    guarantees the real sub-expression pointers reach translate_expression.
    :End Note
    Let binop_data be expr.expr_data
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with binop_data, "operator"
    Let left_expr be proc get from DictPrim with binop_data, "left"
    Let right_expr be proc get from DictPrim with binop_data, "right"
    Let left be translate_expression with left_expr, ctx
    Let right be translate_expression with right_expr, ctx

    Note: Map Erlang operators to HIR operators
    Let hir_op be operator

    Note: Special Erlang operators
    If operator is equal to "!":
        Note: Message send operator
        Return create_hir_send with left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=":
        Note: Pattern match operator
        Return create_hir_match with left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "++":
        Note: List concatenation
        Return create_hir_call with "erlang:append", a list containing left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "--":
        Note: List subtraction
        Return create_hir_call with "erlang:subtract", a list containing left, right

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=:=":
        Set hir_op to "==="  Note: Exact equality

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "=/=":
        Set hir_op to "!=="  Note: Exact inequality

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "andalso":
        Set hir_op to "and"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "orelse":
        Set hir_op to "or"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "div":
        Set hir_op to "/"  Note: Integer division

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "rem":
        Set hir_op to "%"  Note: Remainder

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "band":
        Set hir_op to "&"  Note: Bitwise AND

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bor":
        Set hir_op to "|"  Note: Bitwise OR

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bxor":
        Set hir_op to "^"  Note: Bitwise XOR

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bsl":
        Set hir_op to "<<"  Note: Bit shift left

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bsr":
        Set hir_op to ">>"  Note: Bit shift right
    End If

    Return create_hir_binary_op with hir_op, left, right
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's three unary operators are +, -, not, and bnot. '+' and '-' pass
through unchanged. 'not' becomes '!' to match HIR's boolean negation
spelling, and 'bnot' becomes '~' for bitwise negation. The operator string
substitution is the entirety of the transformation; HIR's unary node form is
otherwise identical.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_unary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Let unop_data be expr.expr_data
    Note:
    expr_data entries read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored "operand"
    handle to a load that returns 0, which would segfault translate_expression.
    :End Note
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with unop_data, "operator"
    Let unary_operand_expr be proc get from DictPrim with unop_data, "operand"
    Let operand be translate_expression with unary_operand_expr, ctx

    Note: Map Erlang unary operators to HIR
    Let hir_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "not":
        Set hir_op to "!"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "bnot":
        Set hir_op to "~"  Note: Bitwise NOT
    End If

    Return create_hir_unary_op with hir_op, operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang calls come in three flavours: local 'foo(args)', remote
'mod:foo(args)' (an explicit ':' operator at the AST level), and higher-order
'F(args)' where F is a function-valued expression. We disambiguate by the
shape of the function position: a ':' op means remote, an atom literal means
local, anything else means higher-order. Local calls are always qualified
with ctx.current_module so HIR consumers see fully-qualified names
everywhere - this matches Erlang's actual runtime behaviour where the VM
resolves bare function names against the calling module.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_call" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data entries are read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored
    "function"/"arguments" handles to a load that returns 0 even though they are
    present, which would feed a null callee/arglist into the translator.
    :End Note
    Let call_data be expr.expr_data
    Let function be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "function"
    Let arguments be proc get from DictPrim with call_data, "arguments"

    Note: Translate arguments
    Let hir_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let hir_arg be translate_expression with arg, ctx
        Add hir_arg to end of hir_args
    End For

    Note:
    All locals that are assigned across the call-shape branches are declared up
    front. Declaring them only inside one branch and reassigning with Set from
    another branch leaves them undefined on the path that skips the declaring
    branch, which the stage1 codegen lowers to a null/garbage slot.
    :End Note
    Let module_name be ""
    Let func_name be ""
    Let qualified_name be ""

    Note: Check if remote call (Module:Function). The operator lookup is bound
    Note: to a local before the compound comparison.
    Let function_type be function.expr_type
    Let function_data be function.expr_data
    Let function_op be proc get from DictPrim with function_data, "operator"
    If function_type is equal to "op" and function_op is equal to ":":
        Let module_expr be proc get from DictPrim with function_data, "left"
        Let func_expr be proc get from DictPrim with function_data, "right"

        Let module_expr_type be module_expr.expr_type
        If module_expr_type is equal to "atom":
            Let module_expr_data be module_expr.expr_data
            Set module_name to proc get from DictPrim with module_expr_data, "value"
        End If

        Let func_expr_type be func_expr.expr_type
        If func_expr_type is equal to "atom":
            Let func_expr_data be func_expr.expr_data
            Set func_name to proc get from DictPrim with func_expr_data, "value"
        End If

        Let module_colon be proc string_concat from StringPrim with module_name, ":"
        Set qualified_name to proc string_concat from StringPrim with module_colon, func_name

        Return create_hir_call with qualified_name, hir_args
    End If

    Note: Local call
    If function_type is equal to "atom":
        Let function_atom_data be function.expr_data
        Set func_name to proc get from DictPrim with function_atom_data, "value"

        Note: Qualify with current module. The current_module field is bound to
        Note: a local before the StringPrim call (stage1 mis-evaluates a
        Note: `obj.field` proc-call argument).
        Let cur_module_name be ctx.current_module
        Let cur_mod_colon be proc string_concat from StringPrim with cur_module_name, ":"
        Set qualified_name to proc string_concat from StringPrim with cur_mod_colon, func_name

        Return create_hir_call with qualified_name, hir_args
    End If

    Note: Higher-order call (function variable)
    Let indirect_func_expr be translate_expression with function, ctx
    Return create_hir_call_indirect with indirect_func_expr, hir_args
End Process

@Reasoning:
'fun' expressions have three syntactic forms: a remote reference
'fun M:F/N' becomes a HIR function reference with qualified name and arity;
a local reference 'fun F/N' is qualified with current_module before becoming
a function reference; an anonymous 'fun(args)->body end' (possibly with
multiple clauses) becomes a lambda. The anonymous case re-uses
translate_clauses_with_dispatch for the body so the clause-dispatch logic is
shared between named functions and anonymous lambdas.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_fun" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    fun_data entries read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored entries
    (notably the "clauses" handle) to a load that returns 0 even though they are
    present.
    :End Note
    Let fun_data be expr.expr_data
    Let fun_type be proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "type"

    Note: Function reference: fun Module:Function/Arity or fun Function/Arity
    If fun_type is equal to "remote_ref":
        Let module_name be proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "module"
        Let func_name be proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "function"
        Let arity be proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "arity"

        Let ref_mod_colon be proc string_concat from StringPrim with module_name, ":"
        Let qualified_name be proc string_concat from StringPrim with ref_mod_colon, func_name

        Return create_hir_function_ref with qualified_name, arity

    Otherwise If fun_type is equal to "local_ref":
        Set func_name to proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "function"
        Set arity to proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "arity"

        Let local_module_name be ctx.current_module
        Let local_mod_colon be proc string_concat from StringPrim with local_module_name, ":"
        Set qualified_name to proc string_concat from StringPrim with local_mod_colon, func_name

        Return create_hir_function_ref with qualified_name, arity
    End If

    Note: Anonymous function with clauses
    If fun_type is equal to "anonymous":
        Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with fun_data, "clauses"

        Note: Build lambda from clauses
        Note: Use first clause to determine arity
        Let first_clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, 0
        Note: Bind the field-access handle before passing it as a proc argument
        Note: (stage1 mis-evaluates a `obj.field` proc-call argument).
        Let first_clause_patterns be first_clause.patterns
        Set arity to proc list_length from ListPrim with first_clause_patterns

        Note: Create parameter list
        Let parameters be a list containing nothing
        For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
            Let arg_i_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with i
            Let param_name be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "arg", arg_i_str
            Add param_name to end of parameters
        End For

        Note: Build lambda body with clause dispatch
        Let lambda_body be translate_clauses_with_dispatch with clauses, parameters, ctx

        Note: Create parameter types
        Let param_types be a list containing nothing
        For i from 0 to arity minus 1:
            Let any_type be create_hir_type with "any", a list containing nothing
            Add any_type to end of param_types
        End For

        Let return_type be create_hir_type with "any", a list containing nothing

        Return create_hir_lambda with parameters, param_types, return_type, lambda_body
    End If

    Note: Default
    Return create_hir_error with "unsupported_fun_type"
End Process

@Reasoning:
'case Expr of Patterns... end' tests Expr against each clause's pattern,
running the body of the first matching clause. We translate to a HIR match
expression with a list of (pattern, guard, body) branches. Each branch
preserves the pattern as a translated HIR pattern (so the match expression
can perform real structural matching, not just equality testing), the guard
sequence (combined into a single boolean via AND), and the translated body
statements. The branches list keeps source order so the first-match
semantics persist into HIR consumers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_case" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    case_data's "scrutinee"/"clauses" entries are read with the canonical
    dictionary `get` primitive rather than the `at key` operator. The stage1
    codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict entries to a load that
    returns 0 even though the entries are present (the primitive `get` returns
    the real handles), which would feed a null scrutinee/clauses into the
    translators below and segfault.
    :End Note
    Let case_data be expr.expr_data
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with case_data, "clauses"

    Note: Build match expression with branches. Clause count computed once into a
    Note: local; While loop with list_get because stage1 mis-evaluates a `For Each`
    Note: over a dict-derived RunaList of typed clause structs.
    Let branches be a list containing nothing
    Let case_clause_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than case_clause_total:
        Let clause_raw be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, ci
        Let clause be clause_raw of type ErlangFunctionClause

        Note: Each clause has pattern, guards, and body. The patterns handle is
        Note: bound before the ListPrim call (stage1 mis-evaluates a `obj.field`
        Note: proc-call argument).
        Let case_clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with case_clause_patterns, 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Note: Translate pattern to HIR pattern
        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern, ctx

        Note: Translate guards to conditions. Outer sequence count precomputed.
        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        Let case_guard_seq_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guards
        Let gsi be 0
        While gsi is less than case_guard_seq_total:
            Let guard_seq be proc list_get from ListPrim with guards, gsi
            Let case_guard_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guard_seq
            Let gi be 0
            While gi is less than case_guard_total:
                Let guard_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_seq, gi
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
                Set gi to gi plus 1
            End While
            Set gsi to gsi plus 1
        End While

        Note: Translate body
        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body, ctx

        Let branch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add branch_info to end of branches
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While

    Note: Scrutinee translated last (mirrors translate_if's ordering). The
    Note: scrutinee handle is bound to a local before the recursive translate
    Note: call (stage1 mis-evaluates a `dict at key` value used inline as a call
    Note: argument across an intervening loop).
    Note: Scrutinee translated last (mirrors translate_if's ordering). The
    Note: scrutinee handle is bound to a local before the recursive translate call.
    Let case_scrutinee_expr be proc get from DictPrim with case_data, "scrutinee"
    Let scrutinee be translate_expression with case_scrutinee_expr, ctx

    Return create_hir_match_expr with scrutinee, branches
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's 'if' is not a binary if/else - it is a sequence of guard-protected
clauses where the first clause whose guards all succeed wins. We translate
to nested HIR if expressions: each clause's guards combine via AND to form a
condition, and the bodies become the then-branches. If no clause matches the
runtime raises if_clause; we do not emit that fallthrough error here because
the if-chain naturally terminates at the last clause's else (or null).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_if" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    "clauses" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the stage1
    codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored clause list to a
    load that returns 0 even though it is present.
    :End Note
    Let if_data be expr.expr_data
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with if_data, "clauses"
    Let clause_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses

    Note:
    Build the right-nested if-chain by folding the clauses from last to first.
    Each clause becomes `if <guard-conjunction> then <body> else <accumulated>`
    where the accumulated else is the chain built from the clauses that follow
    it. The innermost else starts empty (an absent else), matching Erlang's
    behaviour where a non-matching if-chain raises if_clause at runtime - the
    backend materialises that fallthrough. Iterating in reverse means each step
    wraps exactly one outer clause around the already-built remainder, so the
    first clause ends up outermost and is tested first, preserving Erlang's
    first-true-guard-wins ordering.
    :End Note
    If clause_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let accumulated be 0
    Let i be clause_count minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i

        Note: Translate this clause's guard sequence into an AND-combined condition.
        Let condition be 0
        Let dispatch_guards be clause.guards
        Let dispatch_guard_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with dispatch_guards
        If dispatch_guard_count is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be proc list_get from ListPrim with dispatch_guards, 0
            Let guard_conditions be a list containing nothing

            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of guard_conditions
            End For

            Let guard_cond_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guard_conditions
            If guard_cond_total is greater than 0:
                Set condition to proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_conditions, 0
                Let j be 1
                While j is less than guard_cond_total:
                    Let next_guard be proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_conditions, j
                    Set condition to create_hir_binary_op with "and", condition, next_guard
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Note: A guard-less if-clause (degenerate) is unconditionally true.
        If condition is equal to 0:
            Set condition to create_hir_bool with true
        End If

        Let dispatch_body_exprs be clause.body
        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with dispatch_body_exprs, ctx

        Note: The else-body wraps the chain accumulated from following clauses.
        Note: When nothing follows (innermost), the else-body is empty.
        Let else_body be a list containing nothing
        If accumulated is not equal to 0:
            Let else_stmt be create_hir_expr_statement with accumulated
            Add else_stmt to end of else_body
        End If

        Set accumulated to create_hir_if_expr with condition, hir_body, else_body
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return accumulated
End Process

@Reasoning:
'receive ... after T -> ... end' is Erlang's mailbox primitive: the calling
process blocks reading from its mailbox until a message matches one of the
clauses or the timeout T fires. We translate clauses identically to
case-clauses (each becomes a {pattern, guards, body} dictionary), plus an
optional timeout expression and after-body. The HIR receive node is a
first-class construct because no other target language has identical
semantics; backends lower it differently depending on whether they target
actor-model runtimes, channel-based concurrency, or pure thread+queue.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_receive" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data entries read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored handles
    to a load that returns 0 even though they are present.
    :End Note
    Let receive_data be expr.expr_data
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "clauses"
    Let after_timeout be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "after_timeout"
    Let after_body be proc get from DictPrim with receive_data, "after_body"

    Note: Build receive expression
    Let receive_clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each clause in clauses:
        Note: Bind the patterns handle before the ListPrim call (stage1
        Note: mis-evaluates a `obj.field` proc-call argument).
        Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern, ctx

        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_seq in guards:
            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
            End For
        End For

        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body, ctx

        Let clause_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add clause_info to end of receive_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate timeout
    Let hir_timeout be 0
    If after_timeout is not equal to 0:
        Set hir_timeout to translate_expression with after_timeout, ctx
    End If

    Let hir_after_body be a list containing nothing
    If proc list_length from ListPrim with after_body is greater than 0:
        Set hir_after_body to translate_expressions with after_body, ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_receive with receive_clauses, hir_timeout, hir_after_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
'try Body of Patterns... catch Clauses... after AfterBody end' is Erlang's
unified exception construct. We preserve all four sections: the try body,
the optional 'of' clauses that pattern-match the try body's value (when
present, the try succeeds only when an of clause matches), the catch
clauses keyed by exception class (error/exit/throw), and the after body
that always runs for cleanup. Catch clauses carry both a class and a
pattern, which the backend uses to filter exceptions by kind and then
match the exception term itself.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_try" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data entries read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored lists to
    a load that returns 0 even though they are present.
    :End Note
    Let try_data be expr.expr_data
    Let try_body be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "try_body"
    Let of_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "of_clauses"
    Let catch_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "catch_clauses"
    Let after_body be proc get from DictPrim with try_data, "after_body"

    Note: Translate try body
    Let hir_try_body be translate_expressions with try_body, ctx

    Note: Translate of clauses
    Let hir_of_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each clause in of_clauses:
        Note: Bind the patterns handle before the ListPrim call (stage1
        Note: mis-evaluates a `obj.field` proc-call argument).
        Let of_clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with of_clause_patterns, 0
        Let guards be clause.guards
        Let body be clause.body

        Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern, ctx

        Let hir_guards be a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_seq in guards:
            For Each guard_expr in guard_seq:
                Let hir_guard be translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
                Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
            End For
        End For

        Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body, ctx

        Let clause_info be a dictionary containing:
            "pattern" as hir_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add clause_info to end of hir_of_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate catch clauses
    Let hir_catch_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each catch_data in catch_clauses:
        Let exception_class be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_class"
        Let exception_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_pattern"
        Set guards to proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "guards"
        Set body to proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "body"

        Let hir_exception_class be 0
        If exception_class is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_exception_class to translate_expression with exception_class, ctx
        End If

        Let hir_exception_pattern be translate_pattern with exception_pattern, ctx

        Set hir_guards to a list containing nothing
        For Each guard_expr in guards:
            Set hir_guard to translate_expression with guard_expr, ctx
            Add hir_guard to end of hir_guards
        End For

        Set hir_body to translate_expressions with body, ctx

        Let catch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "exception_class" as hir_exception_class,
            "exception_pattern" as hir_exception_pattern,
            "guards" as hir_guards,
            "body" as hir_body
        End Dictionary

        Add catch_info to end of hir_catch_clauses
    End For

    Note: Translate after body
    Let hir_after_body be a list containing nothing
    If proc list_length from ListPrim with after_body is greater than 0:
        Set hir_after_body to translate_expressions with after_body, ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_try with hir_try_body, hir_of_clauses, hir_catch_clauses, hir_after_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
'begin ... end' is Erlang's block expression that groups a sequence of
expressions into one expression whose value is the last sub-expression. We
translate the body via translate_expressions (which handles the
last-expression-is-return convention) and wrap in a HIR block. No special
scope semantics apply because Erlang's begin-end does not introduce a new
binding scope - bindings inside the block escape into the surrounding
scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_begin" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    "body" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the stage1 codegen
    lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored body list to a load that
    returns 0 even though it is present.
    :End Note
    Let begin_data be expr.expr_data
    Let body be proc get from DictPrim with begin_data, "body"
    Let hir_body be translate_expressions with body, ctx

    Note: Begin-end is just a block expression
    Return create_hir_block with hir_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
List comprehensions '[Template || Q1, Q2, ...]' carry one template expression
and a list of qualifiers, each either a generator (Pat <- List) or a filter
(BoolExpr). We translate the template once and each qualifier into a typed
dictionary preserving its kind. Multiple qualifiers are handled either by
the dedicated build_nested_comprehension_loops helper (when there are
several, allowing proper nesting) or inline (single qualifier). The HIR
comprehension node keeps the generator/filter distinction so backends can
either lower to nested loops or use a target language's own comprehension.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_list_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data entries are read through the canonical dictionary `get` primitive
    rather than the `at key` operator: the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key`
    read of these dict-literal-stored handles to a load that returns 0 even
    though the entries are present, which would feed a null template/qualifier
    into the translators and segfault.
    :End Note
    Let lc_data be expr.expr_data
    Let template be proc get from DictPrim with lc_data, "template"
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with lc_data, "qualifiers"

    Note: Build nested loops and filters for comprehension
    Note: [Template || Qualifier1, Qualifier2, ...]

    Note: Translate template
    Let hir_template be translate_expression with template, ctx

    Note:
    Translate every qualifier (generator or filter) in source order into the
    qualifier list of one HIR list-comprehension node. The node carries the
    full ordered qualifier sequence, so a comprehension with several generators
    and filters is represented faithfully regardless of count - the backend
    lowers the ordered qualifiers into the appropriate nested loops/filters.
    No separate multi-qualifier path is needed: a single loop over all
    qualifiers handles one or many uniformly.
    :End Note
    Let hir_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    Note:
    Iterate the qualifier list with an explicit index + list_get rather than a
    For-Each: the For-Each element binding over a dictionary-valued RunaList
    returned from `get` does not carry the live element pointer reliably under
    the stage1 codegen, leaving each qualifier's "type" read empty and dropping
    every qualifier from the comprehension. The indexed While reads each element
    handle directly.
    :End Note
    Let qualifiers_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with qualifiers
    Let qi be 0
    While qi is less than qualifiers_total:
        Let qualifier be proc list_get from ListPrim with qualifiers, qi
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"

        Note:
        The qualifier "type" tag is compared with string_equals (content
        comparison) rather than `is equal to`: the qualifier dictionaries store
        the tag as a parser-local string value, and the stage1 codegen's
        `is equal to` on two String operands tests handle identity, not content,
        so it never matches the literal here and silently drops the qualifier.
        :End Note
        Let qual_is_generator be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "generator"
        Let qual_is_filter be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "filter"

        If qual_is_generator is equal to 1:
            Let pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let list_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "list"

            Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern, ctx
            Let hir_list be translate_expression with list_expr, ctx

            Let gen_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as hir_pattern,
                "list" as hir_list
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_info to end of hir_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_is_filter is equal to 1:
            Let filter_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let hir_filter be translate_expression with filter_expr, ctx

            Let filter_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as hir_filter
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_info to end of hir_qualifiers
        End If
        Set qi to qi plus 1
    End While

    Return create_hir_list_comprehension with hir_template, hir_qualifiers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary comprehensions '<< Template || Q1, Q2, ... >>' are the binary-data
counterpart to list comprehensions, producing a binary instead of a list.
The template is a binary segment dictionary rather than an arbitrary
expression. Qualifiers can be ordinary list generators ('Pat <- List') OR
binary generators ('Pat <= Binary'); we distinguish via qual_type and route
the source through either "list" or "binary" key so the backend knows which
collection kind to iterate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data entries read through the canonical dictionary `get` primitive:
    the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored
    handles to a load that returns 0 even though the entries are present.
    :End Note
    Let bc_data be expr.expr_data
    Let template be proc get from DictPrim with bc_data, "template"
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with bc_data, "qualifiers"

    Note: Similar to list comprehension but produces binary
    Let hir_template be template  Note: Template is segment dict

    Let hir_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator" or qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
            Let pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let source_key be "list"
            If qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
                Set source_key to "binary"
            End If
            Let source_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, source_key

            Let hir_pattern be translate_pattern with pattern, ctx
            Let hir_source be translate_expression with source_expr, ctx

            Let gen_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as qual_type,
                "pattern" as hir_pattern,
                "source" as hir_source
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_info to end of hir_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let filter_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let hir_filter be translate_expression with filter_expr, ctx

            Let filter_info be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as hir_filter
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_info to end of hir_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Return create_hir_binary_comprehension with hir_template, hir_qualifiers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang records are tuples with named field access; we translate them to HIR
record constructions that preserve the record name (for type resolution),
the field/value map, and an optional base record (Erlang's '#Record{X=Y}'
update form). The field map omits fields not explicitly given - they will
take default values from the record definition at the time the HIR is
lowered. The record_def lookup in ctx.records is currently used only for
later type checking; field validation happens during semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_record_create" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    expr_data / field entries read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive;
    the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored
    "fields"/"base"/field "value" handles to a load that returns 0 even though
    they are present.
    :End Note
    Let record_create_data be expr.expr_data
    Let record_name be proc get from DictPrim with record_create_data, "name"
    Let fields be proc get from DictPrim with record_create_data, "fields"
    Let base be proc get from DictPrim with record_create_data, "base"

    Note: Get record definition from context
    Let ctx_records be ctx.records
    Let record_def be proc get from DictPrim with ctx_records, record_name

    Note:
    The field map is built as an ordered LIST of {name, value} dictionary
    literals rather than a name-keyed dictionary. A dynamic-key dictionary
    (Set <dict> at key <variable> ...) does not round-trip through the stage1
    codegen - dict_keys returns an empty key set downstream - so the record
    fields would be silently dropped. An ordered list of literal-keyed field
    dictionaries reads back faithfully. The source fields are walked by index
    (For-Each element bindings over a get-returned RunaList do not carry the
    live element pointer reliably under stage1).
    :End Note
    Let hir_fields be a list containing nothing
    Let record_field_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with fields
    Let rfi be 0
    While rfi is less than record_field_total:
        Let field_data be proc list_get from ListPrim with fields, rfi
        Let field_name be proc get from DictPrim with field_data, "name"
        Let field_value be proc get from DictPrim with field_data, "value"

        Let hir_value be translate_expression with field_value, ctx
        Let hir_field be a dictionary containing:
            "name" as field_name,
            "value" as hir_value
        End Dictionary
        Add hir_field to end of hir_fields
        Set rfi to rfi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Handle record update
    Let hir_base be 0
    If base is not equal to 0:
        Set hir_base to translate_expression with base, ctx
    End If

    Return create_hir_record with record_name, hir_fields, hir_base
End Process

@Reasoning:
'Record#name.field' is Erlang's record field access syntax. We translate the
record expression and pair it with the field name (kept as a string because
record field-to-tuple-index resolution happens during semantic analysis when
the record definition is available). HIR consumers handling record_access
nodes are expected to consult the record definition catalogue separately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_record_access" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    "record"/"field" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; the
    stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored "record"
    handle to a load that returns 0 even though it is present.
    :End Note
    Let record_access_data be expr.expr_data
    Let record be proc get from DictPrim with record_access_data, "record"
    Let field be proc get from DictPrim with record_access_data, "field"

    Let hir_record be translate_expression with record, ctx

    Return create_hir_record_access with hir_record, field
End Process

@Reasoning:
This is the pattern-to-HIR-pattern translator, used by case/receive/try
clauses where the HIR consumer can match patterns structurally rather than
emitting equality tests. It mirrors build_pattern_match (which emits boolean
conditions) but produces actual HIR pattern objects: variables become
var_patterns, literals become literal_patterns, lists become list_patterns
with an optional tail pattern, tuples become tuple_patterns, and the special
"_" wildcard becomes a wildcard_pattern. Unrecognised pattern shapes return
a wildcard so HIR consumers default to "match anything", which keeps
translation partial-safe at the cost of potentially admitting matches the
original Erlang would have rejected.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_pattern" that takes pattern as ErlangExpression and ctx as ErlangTranslationContext returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Note: Translate Erlang pattern to HIR pattern
    Let pattern_data be pattern.expr_data

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "name"
        Return create_hir_var_pattern with var_name
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "value"
        Let atom_literal_kind be "atom_literal"
        Return create_hir_literal_pattern with atom_value, atom_literal_kind
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "value"
        Let int_literal_kind be "int_literal"
        Return create_hir_literal_pattern with int_value, int_literal_kind
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "list":
        Note:
        "elements"/"tail" read via the canonical dictionary `get` primitive; an
        `at key` read of the dict-literal-stored handles returns 0 under stage1.
        :End Note
        Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "elements"
        Let tail be proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "tail"

        Let hir_elements be a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Let hir_elem be translate_pattern with elem, ctx
            Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
        End For

        Let hir_tail be 0
        If tail is not equal to 0:
            Set hir_tail to translate_pattern with tail, ctx
        End If

        Return create_hir_list_pattern with hir_elements, hir_tail
    End If

    If pattern.expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set elements to proc get from DictPrim with pattern_data, "elements"

        Set hir_elements to a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Set hir_elem to translate_pattern with elem, ctx
            Add hir_elem to end of hir_elements
        End For

        Return create_hir_tuple_pattern with hir_elements
    End If

    Note: Default - variable pattern
    Return create_hir_wildcard_pattern
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR CREATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor for HIRType records used wherever the translator needs to embed
a concrete type reference (parameter types, return types, generic
instantiations). The two-field structure (name + type-argument list) is the
minimal representation that supports both monomorphic types like "integer"
and parametric forms like Dict[String, Atom].
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_type" that takes type_name as String, type_args as List[Any] returns HIRType:
    Return a value of type HIRType with
        name as type_name,
        args as type_args
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wraps an atom literal as an HIRExpression. Atoms are distinguished from
other string-valued literals by their kind tag so downstream consumers
(particularly target-language renderers) emit the correct syntactic form -
e.g. ':symbol' in Ruby, ":atom" in Elixir, "Symbol(:foo)" in Racket.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_atom" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "atom",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable reference constructor. The data field carries the source identifier
verbatim; binding resolution is the responsibility of the consumer once the
HIR is paired with a scope analysis pass.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_var" that takes name as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "var",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Integer literal constructor. The Integer type is used directly because
Erlang integers are arbitrary-precision in semantics but typically fit into
machine-word sizes for the translator's purposes; downstream type analysis
may widen the representation later when overflow is provable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_int" that takes value as Integer returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "int",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Float literal constructor. Erlang floats are 64-bit IEEE doubles; we accept
a Float here and emit a HIR float node with the value preserved bit-exactly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_float" that takes value as Float returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "float",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
String literal constructor. Note that Erlang "strings" are actually lists of
integers (Unicode code points) at the language level, but we expose them as
HIR string nodes so the backend can emit native string types where the
target language has them; targets that need to preserve Erlang's
list-of-integers semantics can re-lower at code emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_string" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "string",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Character literal constructor. Erlang's '$X' notation yields the integer
code point of X; we keep the original character form here as a String for
display fidelity, with backends free to lower to integer if their target
language treats characters as integers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_char" that takes value as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "char",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean literal constructor. Erlang booleans are the atoms 'true' and
'false' at the runtime level; we expose them as a distinct HIR kind so
backends with native booleans can emit those directly rather than going
through the atom path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_bool" that takes value as Boolean returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "bool",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Proper-list constructor (no tail). For improper lists 'translate_list'
synthesises a chain of erlang:cons calls via create_hir_call rather than
calling this constructor, so a 'list' HIR node always represents a fully-
materialised proper list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "list",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple constructor for fixed-arity heterogeneous tuples. Distinct from list
so backends can map to native tuple/record types where available; in
languages without tuples the backend lowers to a struct or array.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_tuple" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "tuple",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary literal constructor for Erlang's '<<...>>' bit-syntax. The segments
list preserves each segment's value/size/specifiers as a dictionary so the
backend can reproduce the precise bit-level layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary" that takes segments as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "binary",
        data as segments
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary-operator constructor. The op field carries the post-translation
operator string (after translate_binary_op has normalised Erlang-specific
spellings to HIR spellings), and left/right are the operand HIR
expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary_op" that takes operator as String, left as HIRExpression, right as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let op_data be a dictionary containing:
        "op" as operator,
        "left" as left,
        "right" as right
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "binary_op",
        data as op_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary-operator constructor mirroring create_hir_binary_op but with a single
operand. The op spelling is the post-normalisation HIR form ('!', '~', '-',
'+'), set by translate_unary_op before this constructor is invoked.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_unary_op" that takes operator as String, operand as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let op_data be a dictionary containing:
        "op" as operator,
        "operand" as operand
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "unary_op",
        data as op_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Static call constructor for calls whose target is a fully-qualified
'Module:function' or 'self_module:function' string. The function_name is
pre-qualified by translate_call so consumers do not need to re-resolve
module context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_call" that takes function_name as String, arguments as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Note:
    HIR data dict built as a literal so the backend's `get` reads of "function"
    and "args" return the stored values; incremental "Set at key" stores do not
    round-trip through the stage1 codegen to the backend.
    :End Note
    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function_name,
        "args" as arguments
    End Dictionary

    Let call_kind be "call"
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as call_kind,
        data as call_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indirect call constructor for higher-order calls where the callee is itself
an expression (a function variable, a lambda, the result of another call).
Distinguished from create_hir_call by the kind tag so backends can choose
between direct dispatch and value-level call mechanism.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_call_indirect" that takes function as HIRExpression, arguments as List[HIRExpression] returns HIRExpression:
    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function,
        "args" as arguments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "call_indirect",
        data as call_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Anonymous-function (lambda) constructor. Preserves parameter names, their
types, the return type, and the body statement list. Used both for explicit
'fun(args) -> body end' source and for synthetic lambdas produced when
translating multi-clause anonymous functions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_lambda" that takes parameters as List[String], param_types as List[HIRType], return_type as HIRType, body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let lambda_data be a dictionary containing:
        "parameters" as parameters,
        "param_types" as param_types,
        "return_type" as return_type,
        "body" as body
    End Dictionary

    Let lambda_kind be "lambda"
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as lambda_kind,
        data as lambda_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function reference constructor for the 'fun M:F/N' and 'fun F/N' Erlang
forms. Carries name and arity rather than a callable value so the backend
can decide whether to emit a closure object, a function pointer, or a
delegate depending on its target language idiom.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_function_ref" that takes function_name as String, arity as Integer returns HIRExpression:
    Let ref_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function_name,
        "arity" as arity
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "function_ref",
        data as ref_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Message-send constructor for the Erlang '!' operator. Distinct from a
regular call because the runtime semantics involve enqueueing into a
process mailbox rather than synchronous invocation; backends targeting
actor frameworks lower this to their framework's send primitive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_send" that takes destination as HIRExpression, message as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let send_data be a dictionary containing:
        "destination" as destination,
        "message" as message
    End Dictionary

    Let send_kind be "send"
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as send_kind,
        data as send_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's '=' match operator constructor. Distinct from assignment because
the LHS is a pattern (which may destructure) and the operator can fail at
runtime if the pattern does not match the value. Backends translating to
languages without pattern-match-as-expression lower to a conditional and
an exception throw on mismatch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_match" that takes pattern as HIRExpression, value as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "pattern" as pattern,
        "value" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "match",
        data as match_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Case-expression constructor: holds the scrutinee and a list of
{pattern, guards, body} branches. The branches list is in source order to
preserve first-match semantics. Used by translate_case for Erlang's 'case
... of ... end' construct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_match_expr" that takes scrutinee as HIRExpression, branches as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "scrutinee" as scrutinee,
        "branches" as branches
    End Dictionary

    Let match_expr_kind be "match_expr"
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as match_expr_kind,
        data as match_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
If-expression constructor with explicit then/else statement lists. Used by
translate_if to build the nested chain for Erlang's 'if ... end'. The else
list is empty when the source had no terminating else clause, in which case
the runtime would raise if_clause if no preceding clause matched.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_if_expr" that takes condition as HIRExpression, then_body as List[HIRStatement], else_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let if_data be a dictionary containing:
        "condition" as condition,
        "then" as then_body,
        "else" as else_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "if_expr",
        data as if_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Receive-expression constructor for Erlang's mailbox primitive. Holds the
list of receive clauses (each with pattern+guards+body), an optional
timeout expression, and the after-body statements that run if the timeout
fires. Both timeout and after_body may be 0 when no 'after' clause was
present.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_receive" that takes clauses as List[Any], timeout as HIRExpression, after_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let receive_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses,
        "timeout" as timeout,
        "after" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "receive",
        data as receive_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Try-expression constructor preserving all four sections of Erlang's
try/of/catch/after: the protected body, the 'of' value-match clauses (empty
when absent), the catch clauses keyed by exception class, and the always-
runs after-body. Backends with simpler exception models flatten the of and
catch sections during lowering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_try" that takes try_body as List[HIRStatement], of_clauses as List[Any], catch_clauses as List[Any], after_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Let try_data be a dictionary containing:
        "try" as try_body,
        "of" as of_clauses,
        "catch" as catch_clauses,
        "after" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "try",
        data as try_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Block expression constructor wrapping a statement list. Used for 'begin
... end' and for synthetic blocks produced when an expression context needs
multiple statements. The block value is the value of its last sub-statement.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_block" that takes body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "block",
        data as body
End Process

@Reasoning:
List comprehension constructor preserving template and qualifier list.
Distinct from the binary comprehension constructor only by its kind tag and
the type of the template (full expression here vs. binary-segment dict for
binary comprehensions).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list_comprehension" that takes template as HIRExpression, qualifiers as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "list_comprehension",
        data as comp_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary comprehension constructor; the template is typed Any because it is
a segment dictionary rather than an HIRExpression. Backends recognise the
kind tag and treat the template as bit-syntax rather than ordinary
expression syntax.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_binary_comprehension" that takes template as Any, qualifiers as List[Any] returns HIRExpression:
    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Let binary_comp_kind be "binary_comprehension"
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as binary_comp_kind,
        data as comp_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record-creation constructor for '#name{field=value, ...}' and the update
form '#name{Base|...}'. Base is null for fresh-record creation and non-null
for update; the field map carries only EXPLICITLY-SET fields (omitted
fields default at lower-level lowering).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_record" that takes name as String, fields as Dictionary[String, HIRExpression], base as HIRExpression returns HIRExpression:
    Let record_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name,
        "fields" as fields,
        "base" as base
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "record",
        data as record_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record-access constructor for 'Record#name.field'. The field is held as a
string because resolving it to a tuple slot index requires the record
definition, which is consulted during semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_record_access" that takes record as HIRExpression, field as String returns HIRExpression:
    Let access_data be a dictionary containing:
        "record" as record,
        "field" as field
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "record_access",
        data as access_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Macro reference constructor for '?MACRO_NAME'. The translator does not
expand the macro - it preserves the reference so a separate pre-processing
or expansion pass can substitute the macro body when the macro definitions
table is available.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_macro" that takes name as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "macro",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error sentinel expression used when the translator encounters an unsupported
construct. The kind tag "error" lets HIR consumers either propagate the
error to the user or substitute a runtime exception throw, depending on
their error-handling policy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_error" that takes message as String returns HIRExpression:
    Return a value of type HIRExpression with
        kind as "error",
        data as message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Return-statement constructor. Used in translate_expressions to mark the
last expression in a sequence as the value to return from the enclosing
function/clause.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_return" that takes value as HIRExpression returns HIRStatement:
    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "return",
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Expression-statement constructor. Wraps an expression as a statement so it
appears in a statement-list context where its value is discarded. Required
because HIR statement lists do not accept bare expression values.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_expr_statement" that takes expr as HIRExpression returns HIRStatement:
    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "expr",
        data as expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Assignment-statement constructor producing the "assign" HIR statement the
Erlang backend lowers to a single-shot match binding (Target = Value). Used by
translate_clauses_with_dispatch to rebind a clause's own simple-variable
parameter name to the shared synthetic formal (e.g. `Y = arg0`) when the
clauses disagree on names at a position, so each clause body's references
resolve to a live binding. The data dictionary carries the target and value
HIR expression nodes under the keys generate_assignment reads.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_assign" that takes target as HIRExpression, value as HIRExpression returns HIRStatement:
    Let assign_data be a dictionary containing:
        "target" as target,
        "value" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "assign",
        data as assign_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement-position if constructor (companion to create_hir_if_expr which
produces an if EXPRESSION). Used for clause dispatch in
translate_clauses_with_dispatch where the if must be a top-level statement
rather than a sub-expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_if" that takes condition as HIRExpression, then_body as List[HIRStatement], else_body as List[HIRStatement] returns HIRStatement:
    Let if_data be a dictionary containing:
        "condition" as condition,
        "then" as then_body,
        "else" as else_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type HIRStatement with
        stmt_type as "if",
        data as if_data
End Process

Note: Pattern creation helpers

@Reasoning:
Variable-binding pattern constructor. Used by translate_pattern when an
Erlang variable appears in pattern position; the binding semantics (capture
the matched value into the named slot) is the HIR consumer's job.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_var_pattern" that takes name as String returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "var",
        data as name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Literal pattern constructor for atoms, integers, floats, strings, and
chars in pattern position. Match semantics are exact-equality.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_literal_pattern" that takes value as Any, literal_kind as String returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Note:
    literal_kind ("atom_literal" or "int_literal") is folded into pattern_type
    so the backend reconstructs the correct Erlang literal form (atom vs integer)
    from the tag rather than inspecting the value's runtime type, which the code
    generator cannot dispatch on. The raw value is preserved in data.
    :End Note
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as literal_kind,
        data as value
End Process

@Reasoning:
List-shape pattern constructor with optional cons-tail. The tail captures
the '[H|T]' / '[A,B|T]' forms; for proper-list patterns tail is null.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list_pattern" that takes elements as List[ErlangPatternIR], tail as ErlangPatternIR returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Let list_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as elements,
        "tail" as tail
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "list",
        data as list_data
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple-shape pattern constructor for '{A,B,C}' patterns. Arity matching is
implied by element list length and is the HIR consumer's responsibility to
verify against the scrutinee.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_tuple_pattern" that takes elements as List[ErlangPatternIR] returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "tuple",
        data as elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wildcard pattern constructor. Always matches and binds nothing. Carries
the string "_" as data for source-reconstruction fidelity even though the
match semantics depend only on the pattern_type tag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_wildcard_pattern" returns ErlangPatternIR:
    Return a value of type ErlangPatternIR with
        pattern_type as "wildcard",
        data as "_"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point with the canonical translator name. Delegates to the
fully-named translate_erlang_module_to_hir which does the actual work; this
indirection exists so external callers see a name that matches the module
file convention without losing the more-descriptive internal function name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_erlang_to_hir" that takes erl_module as ErlangModule returns HIRModule:
    Return translate_erlang_module_to_hir with erl_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SOURCE -> HIR PIPELINE BUNDLER
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Erlang lexer exposes a token-at-a-time API (create_erlang_lexer +
next_token) but the parser expects three parallel arrays (token-type
list, lexeme-string list, line-number list). This helper drives the
lexer in a loop and populates the three parallel arrays so the parser
can consume them via its standard create_erlang_parser entry point.

Each iteration calls next_token to obtain a Token record (24 bytes:
type at offset 0, start_pos at offset 8, end_pos at offset 16). The
helper reads the lexer's current_line at offset 24 BEFORE calling
next_token because next_token internally advances past whitespace and
newlines, which would otherwise associate the token with the line that
follows it. Lexemes are reconstructed via string_substring(source,
start, end-start). EOF tokens are appended to the array so the parser's
TOKEN_EOF dispatch fires cleanly at the end of the stream; the loop
then terminates.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Allocates three new lists. Reads the lexer's source pointer (offset 0)
to support lexeme extraction. Loops calling next_token: peeks the
lexer's current_line, then advances. Reads the token's type and span;
extracts the lexeme as a substring. Appends type, lexeme, line into
the three lists. Stops after appending the first TOKEN_EOF (so the
parser sees a sentinel EOF entry). Returns nothing — the lexer's
internal tokens/lexemes/lines fields (offsets 40/48/56) are written
with the three list handles so the wrapper can pass them downstream.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_erlang_to_arrays" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens_list be proc list_create from ListPrim
    Let lexemes_list be proc list_create from ListPrim
    Let lines_list be proc list_create from ListPrim

    Let source_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    Let done be 0
    While done is equal to 0:
        Note: Capture the line of the token BEFORE next_token internally
        Note: skips whitespace / advances. next_token's skip_whitespace pass
        Note: may bump current_line past blank lines that precede the token;
        Note: we still want the line of the token itself, which is what
        Note: lexer.current_line reads as after skip_whitespace.
        proc skip_whitespace_and_comments from ErlangLexer with lexer
        Let line_at_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

        Let token be proc next_token from ErlangLexer with lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Set done to 1
        Otherwise:
            Let ttype be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
            Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

            Let lexeme_len be end_pos minus start_pos
            Let lexeme be 0
            If lexeme_len is greater than 0:
                Set lexeme to proc string_substring from StringPrim with source_ptr, start_pos, lexeme_len
            Otherwise:
                Set lexeme to ""
            End If

            proc list_push from ListPrim with tokens_list, ttype
            proc list_push from ListPrim with lexemes_list, lexeme
            proc list_push from ListPrim with lines_list, line_at_token

            If ttype is equal to ErlangLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Set done to 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Persist the three list handles into the lexer's reserved slots
    Note: (tokens @40, lexemes @48, lines @56) so callers reading the lexer
    Note: state see the populated parallel arrays. Returning 0 lets the
    Note: caller chain to a parser create call without an explicit out-pointer.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, tokens_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, lexemes_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, lines_list
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's
LANG_ERLANG arm. Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: create_erlang_lexer
builds the lexer state from the source string, lex_erlang_to_arrays
populates the lexer's three parallel-array slots by repeatedly invoking
next_token, parse_erlang_module wraps those arrays in an ErlangParser
and parses out an ErlangModule, and translate_erlang_to_hir lowers the
module into HIR.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
lexer = create_erlang_lexer(source); lex_erlang_to_arrays(lexer); reads
tokens/lexemes/lines from the lexer's offset 40/48/56 slots; parser =
create_erlang_parser(tokens, lexemes, lines); module = parse_erlang_module(
parser); return translate_erlang_module_to_hir(module). On lexer
allocation failure the wrapper short-circuits to 0 so downstream stages
don't see a partially-formed module.
@End Implementation
Process called "erlang_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_erlang_lexer from ErlangLexer with source_code
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc lex_erlang_to_arrays with lexer

    Let tokens_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let lexemes_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let lines_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

    Let parser be proc create_erlang_parser from Parser with tokens_list, lexemes_list, lines_list
    Let erl_module be proc parse_erlang_module from Parser with parser
    Return translate_erlang_module_to_hir with erl_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher-facing single-arg facade. The translation.runa LANG_ERLANG arm
calls `erlang_to_hir(source)` — this thin wrapper exposes that name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "erlang_to_hir" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc erlang_to_hir_from_source with source_code
End Process
